- future workshop to assess progress in 2 years</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://jornades.uab.cat/plioclim/</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>960</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>Germany, Federal Republic of</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>EUR</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>Austria</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>de_AT</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>European Geosciences Union Ambassador Award</gtr:description><gtr:end>2013-10-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>European Geosciences Union (EGU)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>7B499C57-94F2-4047-BE35-5B90440F69DC</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2013-08-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We have tested and proved the viability of a new method to reconstruct water temperature below the sea surface (here, we reconstruct the properties of an important water mass - Antarctic Intermediate Water - which connects the high latitudes with the tropics).

We have provided the first continuous record of sea surface temperature evolution from the mid latitudes of the Pacific Ocean spanning the last 4 million years (the only other record which exists is from the Atlantic Ocean). We combine this with the first ever reconstruction of Antarctic Intermediate Water temperatures over the same time interval. We show that a complex evolution of Southern Ocean circulation marks the transition from the warm Pliocene climates of 3-4 million years ago with the large ice ages of the last ~2.7 million years.

We provided the first comprehensive test of whether a seafloor extinction event at ~1 million years ago was because of cooling, changes corrosivity of the water masses, or changing food supply. Our data reject the first two factors, and indicate for the first time that a specific change in phytoplankton (living at the sea surface) probably caused the extinction of around 90 fauna living on the seafloor.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>the results are largely academic at this stage, but we propose several hypotheses which should be tested on how the southern high latitudes have evolved over the last 4 million years. We also present a new hypothesis to explain a seafloor extinction event, which requires testing across multiple sites and with global reach.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>BE56E5D6-6813-4152-8C0F-967C4D96F05D</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/570F14DE-EB83-4979-AEC6-E9C899D63881"><gtr:id>570F14DE-EB83-4979-AEC6-E9C899D63881</gtr:id><gtr:title>Interglacial intensity in the North Atlantic over the last 800 000 years: investigating the complexity of the mid-Brunhes Event</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Quaternary Science</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/9ddae07c139dfae696894272d0f20cc1"><gtr:id>9ddae07c139dfae696894272d0f20cc1</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>CANDY I</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/A86E9169-AC50-46B6-87F6-1361ED39C37F"><gtr:id>A86E9169-AC50-46B6-87F6-1361ED39C37F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Ant